[2] South Africa
Date: Fri 4 Mar 2011
Source: Businessday.co.za [summarised, edited]
<http://www.businessday.co.za/articles/Content.aspx?id=136224>


Onderstepoort to reintroduce foot and mouth vaccine line
--------------------------------------------------------
The government [of South Africa, or SA] is investing in a new
facility to make vaccines against FMD at the Onderstepoort Veterinary
Institute -- which falls under the Agricultural Research Council (ARC)
-- as it moves to reintroduce a capacity lost a decade ago.

Agriculture Minister Tina Joemat-Pettersson said on Monday [28 Feb
2011] exports of cloven-hoofed animals and their products had been
suspended after a "suspected" outbreak of the disease. The suspension
has potentially crippling implications for SA's meat export industry.

The Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute began making FMD in the late
1960s, but stopped in 2005 after its technology became obsolete.

The development of a new local facility will help ensure a close
match between vaccines and the specific strains of the virus
circulating.

Vaccines are used against FMD in some countries including SA, while
others such as the UK opt solely for slaughter.

Prof Jeena said it would cost R250m [USD 36 469 730] to build the new
vaccine manufacturing plant at Onderstepoort, the only facility that
had the necessary bio-safety controls to produce the shots. FMD is
highly contagious and spreads easily between species.

Prof Jeena said livestock in SA was vulnerable to the "Southern
African strain" of FMD, and there were [several] variations
circulating at any one time. The local strain of the disease was more
difficult to work with than strains found in other parts of the world,
as it was less stable, produced lower vaccine yields and had a
shelf-life of no more than a year.

Prof Jeena said Onderstepoort hoped to have a pilot facility set up
"within the next couple of months," and expected to manufacture
emergency stock to deal with an outbreak within the next 18 months.

Onderstepoort's acting programme manager for trans-boundary animal
diseases, Dr Livio Health, said scientists expected to have the
results of their analysis of the strain responsible for the outbreak
in KwaZulu-Natal early next week.

[Byline: Tamar Kahn]

